revision.text:
The '''2023 FIFA Women's World Cup bidding process''' resulted in the Fédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) selecting the joint by country bid as the location for the [[2023 FIFA Women's World Cup]]

These are the bids from countries vying to host the 2023 FIFA's Women's World Cup. The official announcement for which one of these countries will host the Women's World Cup will not be made until early 2019. As of August 2018, Australia is the official bidder and five countries (Japan, Thailand, New Zealand, South Africa and Colombia) have expressed interest in hosting the 2023 FIFA Women's World Cup.

==Official candidates==

* {{AUS}}
{{main|Australia 2023 FIFA Women's World Cup bid}}

In 2017 it was first announced that the Australian Government was funding a feasibility study to host the 2023 Women's World Cup.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-06-13/australia-to-bid-for-2023-football-world-cup/8612060|title=Australia to bid for 2023 Women's World Cup, Federal Government to support FFA|date=13 June 2017|work=ABC News}}</ref> Further funding was put into the bid in early 2018 by Federal Minister for Sport [[Bridget McKenzie]] as the government confirmed they were pledging an extra 4 million for it<ref>{{cite web |title=Federal government commits $4 million to Australia’s 2023 Women’s World Cup bid |url=https://www.news.com.au/sport/breaking-news/federal-government-commits-4-million-to-australias-2023-womens-world-cup-bid/news-story/467868a54c931fe6aa66b7d702190b0b |website=News AU |publisher=News AU |accessdate=13 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Australian Government confirms ongoing support for FIFA Women’s World Cup bid |url=https://matildas.footballaustralia.com.au/news/australian-government-confirms-ongoing-support-fifa-womens-world-cup-bid |website=Football Federation Australia |date=6 February 2018}}</ref> As at October 2018, a bid was being prepared by [[Football Federation Australia|FFA]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.myfootball.com.au/news/westfield-matildas-tickets-selling-fast-penrith-match|title=Westfield Matildas tickets selling fast for Penrith match|publisher=[[Football Federation Australia]]|date=12 October 2018|accessdate=12 October 2018}}</ref> The bid was officially launched on 29 October 2018 with the campaign slogan "#GetOnside".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxsports.com.au/football/matildas/get-onside-the-ffa-launches-its-bid-for-australia-to-host-the-2023-womens-world-cup/news-story/f1cee361ff4135d93f676a342eb5be4c|title=Get Onside: The FFA launches its bid for Australia to host the 2023 Women’s World Cup|work=Fox Sports|date=29 October 2018}}</ref>

==Possible candidates==
* {{JPN}}

Japan bid on 2023 tournament after declining their initial intention to bid on 2019 FIFA Women's World Cup. [[Japan Football Association]] (JFA) Vice president [[Kozo Tashima]] says that the facilities will be renovated and ready for the World Cup.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/sports/2013/12/19/soccer/japan-to-bid-for-2023-womens-world-cup/|title=Japan to bid for 2023 Women’s World Cup|publisher=The Japan Times|date=1 February 2015}}</ref> As of 2018, Japan is still in the running.<ref name="games2023">{{cite web |title=Australian Government release extra funding for 2023 FIFA Women's World Cup bid |url=https://www.insidethegames.biz/articles/1061115/australian-government-release-extra-funding-for-2023-fifa-womens-world-cup-bid |website=Inside the games |publisher=Inside the Games |accessdate=13 August 2018}}</ref>

* {{THA}}

In 2015, [[Football Association of Thailand]] President [[Worawi Makudi]] announced Thailand's plans to consider bidding to host the 2023 tournament.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nationmultimedia.com/sports/Thailand-prepares-to-bid-for-FIFA-Womens-World-Cup-30263108.html|title=Thailand prepares to bid for FIFA Women's World Cup|publisher=The Nation|date=25 June 2015|accessdate=27 June 2015}}</ref> However, Makudi has run into some legal trouble since his announcement which could jeopardize Thailand's chances of hosting the 2023 FIFA Women's World Cup.<ref>{{cite web |title=Only one of the 22 men who voted last time FIFA chose a World Cup |url=https://www.insidethegames.biz/articles/1066086/only-one-of-the-22-men-who-voted-last-time-fifa-chose-a-world-cup-host-remains-on-the-football-bodys-rebranded-council |website=Inside the Games |publisher=Inside the Games |accessdate=13 August 2018}}</ref> Makudi's legal troubles have not yet derailed the bid.<ref name="games2023">{{cite web |title=Australian Government release extra funding for 2023 FIFA Women's World Cup bid |url=https://www.insidethegames.biz/articles/1061115/australian-government-release-extra-funding-for-2023-fifa-womens-world-cup-bid |website=Inside the games |publisher=Inside the Games |accessdate=13 August 2018}}</ref>

*{{NZL}}

Prior to their hosting of the [[2015 FIFA U-20 World Cup]], New Zealand officials expressed interest in bidding for the hosting rights of the 2023 FIFA Women's World Cup.<ref>{{cite web|title=New Zealand Football seek to host Fifa Women's World Cup in 2023|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/nz-teams/68992436/new-zealand-football-seek-to-host-fifa-womens-world-cup-in-2023.html|publisher=stuff.co.nz|accessdate=1 July 2015}}</ref> FIFA's director of tournaments, Colin Smith, called New Zealand a "major contender" to host the Women's World Cup should they bid.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fifa boss welcomes New Zealand's interest in hosting 2023 Women's World Cup|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/world-game/69566178/fifa-boss-welcomes-new-zealands-interest-in-hosting-2023-womens-world-cup|publisher=stuff.co.nz|accessdate=1 July 2015}}</ref>

* {{RSA}}

[[South Africa]]n Vice President Ria Ledwaba has expressed an interest in having South Africa host the 2023 FIFA Women's World Cup. She said this likely decision was made during a meeting but they need to get government on board and some other fixes before they can officially bid on it. The bid is likely to be officially launched after South Africa qualified for the Women's World Cup for the first time in [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup|2019]].<ref>{{cite web |title=SA ready to bid for 2023 FIFA Women’s World Cup‚ says Safa vice president Ledwaba |url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/sport/soccer/2018-06-14-sa-ready-to-bid-for-2023-fifa-womens-world-cup-says-safa-vice-president-ledwaba/ |website=Times Live South Africa |publisher=Times Live South Africa |accessdate=13 August 2018}}</ref>

* {{COL}}

Colombia's earlies interest in hosting the 2023 FIFA Women's World Cup came as early as 2016.<ref>{{cite web |title=Colombia declares interest in staging 2023 Fifa Women's World Cup |url=https://www.sportcal.com/News/Search/105948 |website=Sportcal |publisher=Sportcal |accessdate=13 August 2018}}</ref> [[Colombian Football Federation]] President Ramon J Franco has expressed an intent for Colombia to host the 2023 FIFA Women's World Cup.<ref>{{cite web |title=The murky road ahead for Australia's 2023 Women's FIFA World Cup bid |url=https://www.smh.com.au/sport/the-murky-road-ahead-for-australias-2023-womens-fifa-world-cup-bid-20170613-gwqcih.html |website=SMH Australia |publisher=SMH Australia |accessdate=13 August 2018}}</ref> Colombia has hosted two previous soccer tournaments before but none as big as the 2023 FIFA Women's World Cup.<ref>{{cite news|title=Colombia se postula para ser sede del Mundial Femenino 2023|trans-title=Colombia is postulated to host the 2023 Women's World Cup|url=http://gol.caracoltv.com/futbol-internacional/informaciongeneralfutbol/articulo-345531-colombia-se-postula-para-ser-sede-del-mundial-femenino|access-date=23 August 2016|work=Gol Caracol|date=23 August 2016|language=es}}</ref><ref name="FCF">[http://www.futbolred.com/otras-ligas-de-futbol/federacion-colombiana-de-futbol-presento-la-peticion-de-ser-sede-del-mundial-femenino-2023+16680958 la FCF postula oficialmente la candidatura de Colombia para albergar la Copa Mundial Femenina de Mayores de la FIFA para el 2023] FutbolRed</ref><ref name="FIFACOL">[http://www.goal.com/es-co/news/4583/selecci%C3%B3n-colombia/2016/08/23/26803562/habr%C3%A1-liga-profesional-femenina-en-colombia?ICID=AR_RS_5 Liga Colombiana en 2017 y Mundial Femenino en marcha] GOAL Colombia</ref>

