[[File:The pitch at Lord's Cricket Ground.jpg|upright=1.4|thumb|right|The Lord's slope]] The '''Lord's slope''' is a geographical gradient at [[Lord's Cricket Ground]] in London, England. The slope is in the cricket pitch and runs from the north end of the ground to the south end with a drop of {{convert|2.5|m|abbr=out}}.<ref name=mcc>{{cite web|url=http://www.lords.org/news/our-blogs/the-cricket-history-blog/father-time-and-the-lords-slope/ |title=Father Time and the Lord's slope |publisher=MCC |date=2014-01-28 |accessdate=2015-01-01}}</ref>
== History == The land on which Lord's was built was originally near a duck pond on a hill in [[St. John's Wood]]. It was leased by [[Thomas Lord]] following a request from [[George Finch, 9th Earl of Winchilsea]] to find a location where cricket could be played in relative privacy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/caaa0342-7261-11de-ba94-00144feabdc0.html |title=Grounded on terra firma |work=Financial Times |accessdate=2015-01-01}}</ref> Lord's was built around the slope and was enclosed by stands. In the 21st century, there were calls for the slope to be levelled as a result of the advent of [[drop-in pitch]]es.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/cricket/4776895/Slopes-future-in-balance.html |title=Slope's future in balance |work=Telegraph |date=2001-05-19 |accessdate=2015-01-01}}</ref> Smaller ridges in the pitch had previously been removed by surveyors.<ref> *{{cite web|url=http://www.itnsource.com/shotlist//RTV/1961/06/27/BGY504080326/?s=* |title=Cricket: Experts Probe Controversial Lord'S Pitch |publisher=ITN |date=2014-12-25 |accessdate=2015-01-01}} *{{cite web|last=Whelan |first=Charlie |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/cricket/international/england/3005748/Flying-the-flag-for-MCC-members-club.html |title=Flying the flag for MCC members' club |work=Telegraph |date=2014-05-16 |accessdate=2015-01-01}}</ref> However, the [[Marylebone Cricket Club]] rejected these calls stating that removal of the slope would require rebuilding of Lord's and would mean that the ground would be unable to host [[Test cricket]] for five years as the new pitch would need time to mature after the levelling.<ref name=mcc /> In 2002, the Lord's outfield was replaced and drainage installed. During this work, several small deviations in the pitch were removed, but the slope remained.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pitchcare.com/magazine/mallinsons-win-bali-principal-award.html |title=Mallinsons win BALI Principal Award |work=Pitchcare Magazine |date=2003-11-27 |accessdate=2015-01-01}}</ref> During the [[2012 Summer Olympics]], when Lord's hosted the Archery tournament, there were suggestions that the slope would affect the archers. However, British archer [[Alison Williamson]] rejected this, stating that the slope was barely noticeable.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/archery/9408398.stm |title=British archer Alison Williamson not worried by slope |publisher=BBC Sport |date=2011-02-28 |accessdate=2015-01-01}}</ref>
== Cricket == The Lord's slope is often used to advantage by bowlers in cricket matches at Lord's. Because of the slope's angles, [[Seam bowling|seam bowlers]] from the [[Lord's Pavilion|Pavilion End]] and [[Swing bowling|swing bowlers]] from the Nursery End gain an advantage as the natural variation of the slope alters the bounce of the ball when bowling.<ref>{{cite web|author=Geoffrey Boycott |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/columnists/geoffreyboycott/2383325/Harmisons-seamers-hold-key-to-exploiting-Lords-slope.html |title=Harmison's seamers hold key to exploiting Lord's slope |work=Telegraph |date= |accessdate=2015-01-01}}</ref> The gradient of the slope is noted to affect right-handed batsmen more than left-handed batsmen as the ball naturally moves towards left-handed batsmen.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/cricket/henry-blofeld-hoggard-and-harmison-fall-foul-of-lords-slippery-slope-61394.html |title=Henry Blofeld: Hoggard and Harmison fall foul of Lord's slippery slope |work=The Independent |date=2004-05-21 |accessdate=2015-01-01}}</ref> Despite the advantages the slope gives to bowlers, some batsmen consistently make high scores when playing at Lord's.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/cricket/international/england/10899005/Joe-Root-uses-some-sibling-rivalry-to-complete-historic-double-hundred-for-England-against-Sri-Lanka-at-Lords.html |title=Joe Root uses some sibling rivalry to complete historic double hundred for England against Sri Lanka at Lord's |work=Telegraph |date=2014-05-16 |accessdate=2015-01-01}}</ref>
